    "body": "Also, it seems too strict and not allow for exceptions. For example if something is out-of-scope for a pull request, but still should be done in the long term, a TODO seems appropriate. Especially when the TODO is clearly motivated and clearly explains how to fix it.\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n* `boost::thread a; // TODO switch to C++11 std::thread, when possible`\r\n* `GetCounter(); // TODO add lock annotation when class has been updated to our annotated mutex` (e.g. https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/pull/17443#discussion_r425656746)\r\n* ...\r\n\r\nThe advantage of inline TODO is that when the code gets removed or the TODO gets fixed, it will go away in the same commit. If it was filed as an issue, we'd have to walk the issue list and keep it in sync.\r\n\r\nHowever, for general, non actionable TODOs, an issue makes sense. For example \"increase encapsulation\" or \"increase performance with cache\".\r\n\r\nThoughts?",
